# Architect OS — Execution Layer
## Detailed Functional Spec: Five-Page Experience

**Document Type:** Functional Specification — Pre-Build
**Follows:** `ArchitectOS_Execution_Layer_Vision.md`
**Purpose:** Define the specific features, components, interactions, data sources, and decision points for each of the five execution layer pages. This document bridges the conceptual vision and the Antigravity build prompts.

---

## Page 1 — Sprint Launch

### Page Purpose
The Sprint Launch page is generated at sprint lock and serves as the official opening artifact of the quarter. It is the team alignment document, the executive summary, and the founding record of the sprint — all in one. It lives permanently in the execution section and is accessible for the full duration of the sprint and beyond.

### Trigger & Routing
- Generated automatically when the founder clicks "Confirm Lock" in the Sprint Lock Review flow
- Accessible via Execution > Sprint Launch in the navigation
- If no sprint has been locked yet, the page renders an empty state: *"Your Sprint Launch summary will appear here once you lock your sprint plan."* with a link back to Planning
- If a sprint is locked, this page always reflects the locked sprint state — not the current editable state

### Page Layout

**Top Section — Sprint Identity Bar**
A persistent header block that establishes the quarter's identity. Contains:
- Quarter label (e.g., "Q1 2026")
- Sprint goal statement — full text, styled prominently
- Sprint Theme — the AI-generated one-line distillation of the quarter's intent
- Date range of the sprint
- Lock date and time — "Sprint locked on [date]"
- Status badge: ACTIVE / CLOSED

**Primary Content — Executive Summary**
The main body of the page. Two columns:

Left column (wider):
- Executive Summary narrative — AI-generated, three paragraphs
  - Paragraph 1: Context — where this agency is, what stage they are at, why this quarter matters
  - Paragraph 2: Plan — what the sprint contains at a high level, which capability areas are being prioritized and why, what the 3P classification reflects about their strategic intent
  - Paragraph 3: What success looks like — what will be meaningfully different about the agency if this sprint is executed well
- Sprint Plan Summary — a structured breakdown of the full 3P classification:
  - PRIORITIZE section: three capability areas, each showing initiative names and owner
  - PLANT section: three capability areas, each showing initiative names
  - PROGRESSIVELY ITERATE section: three capability areas, each showing initiative name
  - Total initiative count and total milestone count

Right column (narrower):
- Sprint Stats block:
  - Total initiatives: [N]
  - Total milestones: [N]
  - Team members involved: [N]
  - Days in sprint: [N]
- Team block: avatar + name for each team member involved in the sprint, with initiative count next to their name
- Capability Score block: maturity scores for each of the 9 selected capability areas at time of sprint lock — these are the baseline scores. They will not update on this page — they are the locked starting point for retrospective comparison.

**Bottom Section — Share & Export**
- "Share with Team" button — generates a shareable link or PDF export of the executive summary
- "Edit Summary" button — allows the founder to make manual edits to the AI-generated narrative before sharing. Edits are saved but do not affect the underlying sprint data.
- "Regenerate Summary" button — triggers a new GPT synthesis if the founder wants a different framing. Previous version is preserved with a timestamp.

### AI Behavior on This Page
GPT generates three outputs at sprint lock:

**Input context provided to GPT:**
- Sprint goal (verbatim)
- All 9 capability areas with their 3P classification
- All initiative names, success definitions, and owners
- All milestone names and target months
- Founder's AE Ladder stage
- Maturity scores for each selected capability area
- Agency profile data (size, revenue range, team size — from Agency Snapshot)

**Outputs:**
1. Executive Summary (three paragraphs as described above)
2. Sprint Theme (one line — distillation of the quarter's strategic intent)
3. Sprint Theme Close placeholder — stored now, used at retrospective close

**Regeneration behavior:**
The founder can regenerate the full summary or individual paragraphs. Each generation is timestamped. The most recent approved version is the one displayed and shareable.

### Data Sources
| Element | Source |
|---|---|
| Sprint goal | sprint_goals table |
| 3P classifications | sprint_capability_selections table |
| Initiatives and owners | initiatives table |
| Milestones | milestones table |
| Maturity scores (locked) | capability_scores table — snapshot at lock time |
| Team members | team_members table |
| AI narrative | GPT synthesis — stored in sprint_summaries table |

### Empty & Edge States
- Pre-lock: empty state with CTA to complete sprint planning
- Post-lock, pre-share: page visible to founder only
- Post-share: shared link renders a read-only version of the summary without the edit/regenerate controls
- Sprint closed (retrospective complete): page remains accessible, status badge updates to CLOSED, a link to the retrospective appears at the top

